###########################################################################################################################################################

Individual Pod Traffic	vethXXXX	Shows traffic entering/leaving a single specific Pod. Great for isolating one application's noise.
Encapsulation (VXLAN)	virbr0	Shows the Outer Envelope. This is the physical (or VM) wire where Pod data is wrapped in UDP 8472.
NodePort / External	wlo1	Shows North-South traffic. Traffic hitting your machine from your WiFi/LAN.
Pod-to-Pod (Same Node)	cni0	The Switch. Shows all traffic moving between different pods hosted locally on Node 1.
Pod-to-Pod (Cross Node)	flannel.1	The Gateway. Shows traffic that Flannel has already "unwrapped" before handing it to the Pods.
Container-to-Container	lo (Loopback)	The Internal Pipe. Shows traffic between two containers sharing the same Pod (e.g., your httpd and ubuntu).

########################################################################################################################################################
This guide builds the network from the bottom up: starting with physical interfaces, then bridges, then virtual interfaces, and finally the isolated Pod network namespaces.
Phase 1: Physical & Host Infrastructure (node1 Root Namespace)

First, we configure the existing physical interfaces on your host machine to match the state in your ip a snapshot.

    Set the Loopback interface (lo [1]) up:

ip link set lo up

Ensure the physical LAN (eno2 [2]) is DOWN:

ip link set eno2 down

Configure the WiFi (wlo1 [3]) interface:
We assign the specific IP and bring the link up.

ip addr add 172.20.10.3/28 dev wlo1
ip link set wlo1 up

Create the KVM/VM Bridge (virbr0 [4]):
This bridge is the backbone for your hosted VM nodes (Node 2 & 3). We create it, assign the gateway IP, and bring it up.
    ip link add virbr0 type bridge
    ip addr add 192.168.122.1/24 dev virbr0
    ip link set virbr0 up

    Note: The vnet0 [5] and vnet1 [6] interfaces are created automatically by KVM/Libvirt when your VM nodes start, but you can manually add them to the bridge using ip link set vnetX master virbr0 if testing.

Phase 2: CNI & Flannel Overlay (node1 Root Namespace)

Next, we build the Kubernetes-specific local switch (cni0) and the Flannel VXLAN tunnel gateway (flannel.1).

    Create the CNI Bridge (cni0 [8]):
    This is the "switch" that plugs all your local veth interfaces together.

ip link add cni0 type bridge
ip addr add 10.244.0.1/24 dev cni0
ip link set cni0 up

Create the Flannel Gateway (flannel.1 [7]):
This is the most complex command. It creates a VXLAN interface (ID 1), binds it to your local IP (172.20.10.3 on wlo1), and sets the default VXLAN port to 8472.

    ip link add flannel.1 type vxlan id 1 local 172.20.10.3 dev wlo1 dstport 8472
    ip addr add 10.244.0.0/32 dev flannel.1
    ip link set flannel.1 up

Phase 3: Isolated Pod Namespaces & VETH Conduits

Now we create the isolated "rooms" for your pods and use "veth pairs" (the virtual cables) to plug them into the cni0 bridge.
Example 1: Nginx Pod 1 (-fm6td - links to iflink 18)

    Create the Namespace:

ip netns add podA

Create the VETH Pair:
This creates a cable with two ends: vethA (Host side) and eth0A (Pod side).
ip link add vethA type veth peer name eth0A

Connect the Host side (vethA):
We plug it into the cni0 bridge and bring it up.

ip link set vethA master cni0
ip link set vethA up

Connect the Pod side (eth0A):
We push this end of the cable into the podA namespace, rename it to eth0, and configure its IP (we will use 10.244.0.5 as an example).

    ip link set eth0A netns podA
    ip netns exec podA ip link set eth0A name eth0
    ip netns exec podA ip addr add 10.244.0.5/24 dev eth0
    ip netns exec podA ip link set eth0 up

Example 2: Pod with Sidecar (pod-internal-demo)

    Create the Namespace:

ip netns add podSidecar

Create and Connect the VETH Pair (repeat the process above):

ip link add vethS type veth peer name eth0S
ip link set vethS master cni0
ip link set vethS up
ip link set eth0S netns podSidecar
ip netns exec podSidecar ip link set eth0S name eth0
ip netns exec podSidecar ip addr add 10.244.0.6/24 dev eth0
ip netns exec podSidecar ip link set eth0 up

Verify the lo Loopback [CRITICAL for sidecar demo]:
Inside the sidecar namespace, the lo interface must be explicitly brought UP to allow localhost communication.

    ip netns exec podSidecar ip link set lo up

Phase 4: Verification

To confirm that your manual reconstruction matches your original ip a snapshot:

    Check the Host Namespace:
    ip a (Compare this to your original output).

    Check Inside a Pod Namespace:
    ip netns exec podA ip a (Ensure you see eth0 with the 10.244.0.X IP).

    Test Internal Pod Connectivity:
    Try to ping from your host to the Pod IP: ping 10.244.0.5.


