##############################################################################################################################################################

1. Inside Pod with Sidecar (Localhost)

Since containers in a Pod share the same network stack, they communicate over the loopback (lo) interface.

  
    kubectl exec <pod-name> -c <container-name> -- tcpdump -i lo -U -w - | wireshark -k -i -

    What to look for: Filter by http or the specific port (e.g., tcp.port == 80). You will see the source and destination IPs as 127.0.0.1.

2. Pod A (Node 1) to Pod B (Node 2) - Overlay

To see the Overlay (Inner) traffic, you sniff the Pod's interface. To see the VXLAN (Outer) traffic, you sniff the host's VM bridge.

A. To see the "Clean" Pod Traffic (Inner):

kubectl exec <pod-on-node-2> -- tcpdump -i eth0 -U -w - | wireshark -k -i -

    What to look for: You will see the direct Pod-to-Pod IP communication (e.g., 10.244.1.5 → 10.244.2.10).

B. To see the "Encapsulated" VXLAN Traffic (Outer):
Run this from your host (node1) to capture the UDP-wrapped packets on the VM bridge:

sudo tcpdump -i virbr0 udp port 8472 -U -w - | wireshark -k -i -

    What to look for: Look for VXLAN protocol packets. You will see Node 1's IP talking to Node 2's IP. Expand the VXLAN header in Wireshark to see the Pod traffic hidden inside.

3. Services (VIP, NodePort, LB)

This demonstrates how Kubernetes handles Destination NAT (DNAT) and Source NAT (SNAT).

A. ClusterIP / VIP (Internal Load Balancing):
Sniff on the destination Pod while a client calls the Service VIP:

kubectl exec <nginx-pod> -- tcpdump -i eth0 -U -w - | wireshark -k -i -

    What to look for: Even though the client called the VIP (e.g., 10.96.x.x), Wireshark will show the packet arriving at the Pod's actual IP.

B. NodePort (External Access):
Sniff on your physical interface (wlo1) to see the request arrive:

sudo tcpdump -i wlo1 port 30080 -U -w - | wireshark -k -i -

    What to look for: You will see your physical machine's IP as the source and the Node's IP as the destination on port 30080.

4. Service Discovery (DNS)

Before a Pod can call a service by name, it must ask CoreDNS for the IP address.


kubectl exec <client-pod> -- tcpdump -i eth0 udp port 53 -U -w - | wireshark -k -i -

The Trigger: Inside the pod, run nslookup nginx-service.

What to look for: Look for DNS protocol query/response. You will see the Pod asking the CoreDNS Service IP for the "A record" of your service.




